%[text] %[text:anchor:T_6242F60F] # Customize VTOL UAV Configuration
%[text] This topic describes the subsystems and supporting files of the VTOL UAV controller template that you can customize.
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_535CD513] ## Getting Started
%[text] To open the example live script and the directory that contains the Simulink® project file, first run `openExample('uav/CustomizeVTOLConfigurationForYourApplicationExample')` in the Command Window.
%[text] You must open the `VTOLRefApp.prj` project file to access the Simulink model, supporting files, and project shortcuts that this example uses.
% Open the Simulink project
prj = openProject("VTOLApp/VTOLRefApp.prj");
%[text] To set up the aircraft plant model and base controller, click the **Set up Plant** button in the project shortcuts or run the `setupPlant` helper function.
setupPlant %[output:194984d6]
%[text] ![VTOL UAV tilt-rotor model.](text:image:13e4)
%[text] The `VTOLTiltrotor` Simulink model contains these subsystems that enable you to customize the VTOL UAV template:
%[text] - `Ground Control Station` — Contains a customized mission, and sends the next state of the mission to the UAV to enable the VTOL UAV to execute a set of maneuvers.
%[text] - `Autopilot` — The controller for the VTOL aircraft.
%[text] - `Digital Twin` — The dynamic model of the VTOL, including aerodynamics and propulsion.
%[text] - `Visualization` — Visualizes the UAV trajectory.  \
%[text] By default, the VTOL UAV controller template models a tilt rotor, where the front rotors can tilt to transition from hover mode to fixed-wing flight.
%[text] ![Render of a tilt-rotor VTOL UAV.](text:image:9c6e)
%[text] Open the `VTOLTiltrotor` Simulink model.
open_system("VTOLTiltrotor")
%%
%[text] ## **Customize VTOL UAV Plant Model**
%[text] Open the `Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics` subsystem.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath("VTOLTiltrotor/Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics");
open(blockpath)
%[text] ![UAV Dynamics subsystem, which references the VTOLDynamics model](text:image:2091)
%[text] By default, the `Digital Twin` subsystem models the VTOL UAV in a tilt-rotor configuration. However, you can change the VTOL UAV to a different configuration.
%[text] The `UAV Dynamics` subsystem is a model reference, which references the `VTOLDynamics` model. The `VTOLDynamics` model contains the `Forces and Moments` subsystem, which enables you to customize the dynamics of the VTOL UAV plant model. The `Forces and Moments` subsystem represents the kinematics of the VTOL UAV by using the [6DOF (Euler Angles)](docid:aeroblks_ug#f1-791506) block to determine body position, velocity, attitude, and related values. 
%[text] Open the `Forces and Moments` subsystem. 
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics","VTOLDynamics/Force and Moments"]);
open(blockpath)
%[text] ![Force and Moments subsystem.](text:image:1b9b)
%[text] The `Forces and Moments` subsystem takes the `Actuator` and `CtrlSurfaces` signals as input and produces force and torque that it passes to the 6DOF (Euler Angles) block.
%[text] ### Aerodynamic Forces
%[text] Open the `Aerodynamic Forces` subsystem.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics", "VTOLDynamics/Force and Moments/Aerodynamic Forces"]);
open(blockpath);
%[text] ![Aerodynamic Forces subsystem.](text:image:56bc)
%[text] The `Compute Air Data` subsystem calculates the air data which consists of angle of attack, sideslip angle, airspeed, and dynamic pressure. The `Compute Body Frame Forces and Moments` subsystem uses the air data, control surface angles, velocity in the body axes, and body angular velocities to calculate the aerodynamic forces in body frame.
%[text] Open the `Wind frame F& M` subsystem which is located inside the `Compute Body Frame Forces and Moments` subsystem.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics", "VTOLDynamics/Force and Moments/Aerodynamic Forces/Compute Body Frame  Forces and Moments/Wind frame F& M"]);
open(blockpath);
%[text] ![Wind frame F& M subsystem](text:image:1ce9)
%[text] This subsystem calculates the aerodynamic force and moments in the wind frame. You can plug the aerodynamic model of your VTOL UAV into the Lateral Channel and Longitudinal Channel subsystems. 
%[text] ### Propulsion
%[text] Open the `Propulsion` subsystem.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics", "VTOLDynamics/Force and Moments/Propulsion"]);
open(blockpath);
%[text] ![Propulsion subsystem](text:image:2edc)
%[text] The `Propulsion` subsystem models the motor, rotor, and tilt dynamics of the VTOL UAV. In this subsystem, each `rotor assembly` subsystem models the propeller dynamics for the corresponding motor-propeller pair. 
%[text] By default, the `Propulsion` subsystem models the UAV in a tilt-rotor configuration, where the front two rotors (in sections `Rotor 1` and Rotor `2`) can rotate to a vertical position during takeoff or landing, and to a horizontal position during fixed-wing flight. 
%[text] ### Wind Model
%[text] The `Weather Model` subsystem of the `VTOLTiltrotor.slx` allows you to simulate the effect of various wind models on the UAV. You can choose between `Simple Model` or `Weather Model` variant subsystem.
%[text] #### Simple Model
%[text] Open the Simple Model `Model` subsystem.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics", "VTOLDynamics/Force and Moments/Weather Model/Weather Model"]);
open(blockpath);
%[text] ![Simple model subsystem.](text:image:877e)
%[text] Choose this variant subsystem to simulate the effect of wind with constant magnitude and direction. You can customize the wind magnitude and direction by specifying the input to the `Wind_e` signal. For example, a value of `[10 5 0]` corresponds to a wind velocity of 10 m/s, 5 m/s, and 0 m/s in the inertial frame X, Y, and Z direction, respectively.
%[text] To select this variant subsystem, run `Wind=0` in the Command Window.
%[text] #### Weather Model
%[text] Open the `Weather Model` subsystem.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Digital Twin/UAV Dynamics", "VTOLDynamics/Force and Moments/Weather Model/Weather Model"]);
open(blockpath);
%[text] ![Weather model subsystem.](text:image:12d8)
%[text] Choose this variant subsystem to simulate the effect of wind model with higher complexity. By default, the subsystem uses a combination of [Horizontal Wind](docid:aeroblks_ug#f1-1042497) and [Dryden Wind Turbulence Model](docid:aeroblks_ug#f1-1071344) blocks. You can replace the default wind model blocks with other wind models, such as [Discrete Wind Gust Model](docid:aeroblks_ug#f1-1023933), [Wind Shear Model](docid:aeroblks_ug#f1-755049), or implement your own wind model.
%[text] To select this variant subsystem, run `Wind=1` in the Command Window.
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_CDEDD12E] ## Customize **VTOL UAV** Control System
%[text] After modifying the VTOL UAV plant dynamics, you must also update the control system to accommodate the modified VTOL UAV configuration. To customize the autopilot control system, first examine the layout of the controller in the `Autopilot` subsystem.
%[text] Within the `Autopilot` subsystem, the `Controller` subsystem references the `VTOLAutopilotController` model. Open the `Low level controller`.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Autopilot/Controller","VTOLAutopilotController/Low level controller"]);
open(blockpath)
%[text] ![Low level controller subsystem.](text:image:7bb6)
%[text] ### **Control Scheduling**
%[text] You can customize the controller for the VTOL UAV during hover mode by modifying the `Multicopter Controller` subsystem. Similarly, you can customize the fixed-wing mode controller by modifying the `Fixed Wing Controller` subsystem. To customize the blending of the two controllers based on the flight state of the VTOL UAV, modify the `Scheduler` subsystem.
%[text] You can modify the tilt transition controller in the `Tilt Scheduler` subsystem to control the tilt behavior of the front rotors while the VTOL aircraft is in the transition and back transition flight modes.
%[text] ### **Flight State Input**
%[text] The `FlightState` input signal specifies one of the four distinct flight modes of the VTOL UAV, based on the value of the `flightState` variable. You can modify the `flightState` variable by running one of setup helper functions, such as `setupHoverConfiguration`. 
%[text] The flight modes and their corresponding `flightState` values are:
%[text] - Hover — `0`
%[text] - Transition — `1`
%[text] - Fixed Wing — `2`
%[text] - Back Transition — `3` \
%[text] ### **Output Bus Interface**
%[text] The `Digital Twin` subsystem receives control output signals grouped together into signal buses. By default, the VTOL UAV uses the rotor control bus and fixed-wing control bus.
%[text] The default rotor control bus consists of these signals: 
%[text] - `w1` — Rotor 1 PWM
%[text] - `w2` — Rotor 2 PWM
%[text] - `w3` — Rotor 3 PWM
%[text] - `w4` — Rotor 4 PWM
%[text] - `Tilt1` — Rotor 1 tilt PWM
%[text] - `Tilt2` — Rotor 2 tilt PWM \
%[text] The default fixed-wing control bus consists of these signals: 
%[text] - `dA` — Aileron angle in radians
%[text] - `dE` — Elevator angle in radians
%[text] - `dR` — Rudder angle in radians
%[text] - `dT` — Throttle control for Rotor 1 and Rotor 2 in fixed-wing flight \
%[text] If you modify the control surface and rotor layout, you must adjust the fixed-wing and rotor control output bus interface accordingly by modifying the `exampleHelperDefineDigitalTwinInterface` helper file.
%[text] To view and modify the `exampleHelperDefineDigitalTwinInterface.m` helper file, enter this command.
edit("exampleHelperDefineDigitalTwinInterface.m")
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_CDEDD12E] ## Customize Flight Mission
%[text] You can customize your flight mission using the supported mission modes of the [Path Manager](docid:uav_ref#mw_755010f7-0704-4c3d-9f31-3109be5b95b7) block. 
%[text] This table lists the mission modes, the associated action for each, and their corresponding VTOL UAV flight modes.
%[text:table]
%[text] | Mode | Action | Supported Flight Mode |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | 1 | Vertical takeoff | Hover |
%[text] | 2 | Waypoint following | Hover, Fixed Wing |
%[text] | 3 | Orbiting waypoint | Hover, Fixed Wing |
%[text] | 4 | Vertical landing | Hover |
%[text] | 6 | Transition between hover and fixed-wing Mode | Hover, Fixed Wing |
%[text:table]
%[text] Note that mode 5 has been omitted because it corresponds return to launch mode which this model does not use.
%[text] You can modify the `exampleHelperTransitionMissionData.m` helper file to create a new VTOL UAV mission. By default, the helper file contains a mission with these parts:
%[text] 1. Takeoff vertically
%[text] 2. Hover to two waypoints
%[text] 3. Transition to fixed-wing flight mode
%[text] 4. Fly to a waypoint
%[text] 5. Orbit a waypoint
%[text] 6. Transition to hover flight mode
%[text] 7. Land vertically \
%[text] Open the `exampleHelperTransitionMissionData.m` helper file.
edit('exampleHelperTransitionMissionData.m')
%%
%[text] ## Customize **VTOL UAV** Guidance Logic
%[text] Open the `Guidance Mode Selector` subsystem.
blockpath = Simulink.BlockPath(["VTOLTiltrotor/Autopilot/Controller", ...
    "VTOLAutopilotController/Guidance Test Bench/ControlType/Guidance Testbench/Guidance Logic/Guidance Stateflow/Guidance Mode Selector"]);
open(blockpath);
%[text] ![](text:image:33ad)
%[text] This stateflow diagram determines the high level control logic that the low level controller uses, and you can plug your custom VTOL UAV guidance logic into this stateflow diagram. This subsystem calculates the setpoint of the low level controller during various flight modes, such as takeoff, forward transition, waypoint navigation, orbit, backward transition, and landing. In addition, the logic determines the conditions in which the modes change during the mission.
%[text] For instance, this part of the diagram controls the guidance logic of the UAV before in the pre transition phase. 
%[text] ![](text:image:385f)
%[text] In this phase, the guidance logic activates the airspeed and altitude controller, the attitude controller, and the course control in fixed-wing mode. It then sets these setpoints for the airspeed, altitude, and course controllers:
%[text] - L1 distance — 25 meter
%[text] - Airspeed — 14 m/s
%[text] - Altitude — present altitude
%[text] - Course — present course \
%[text] After 5 seconds, the guidance logic then starts the back transition mode.
%[text] ### **Control Modes Output**
%[text] The `Guidance Mode Selector` subsystem outputs the `ctrlMode` bus which contains various flags that is used by the low level controller subsystems. By default, the bus contains these elements:
%[text] - `TransitionCondition` — Flag that indicates to the autopilot when it is safe to fully switch to fixed-wing control during forward transition.
%[text] - `inTransition` —  Flag that indicates to the autopilot that the UAV is in transition.
%[text] - `lateralGuidance` — Flag that activates the fixed wing lateral guidance in the low level controller subsystem.
%[text] - `airspeedAltitude` — Flag that activates the fixed wing airspeed and altitude guidance in the low level controller subsystem.
%[text] - `attitude` — Flag that activates the fixed wing attitude guidance in the low level controller subsystem. \
%[text] ### Autopilot Setpoints Output
%[text] The `Guidance Mode Selector` subsystem outputs several buses which contains various setpoints for the low level low level controller subsystems. By default, `Guidance Mode Selector` subsystem outputs these buses:
%[text] - `InnerLoopCmds` — X, Y, Z, and yaw angle setpoints.
%[text] - `aacSP` — Airspeed, altitude, course, L1, climb rate setpoints.
%[text] - `FixedWingSP` — Roll, pitch, yaw airspeed setpoints. \
%[text] ### Guidance Logic Control Interface
%[text] If you use a custom guidance logic with a different control mode flags or autopilot setpoint outputs, you must adjust the output bus definitions by modifying the `exampleHelperDefineCtrlInterface.m` helper file.
%[text] To view and modify the `exampleHelperDefineCtrlInterface.m` helper file, enter this command.
edit("exampleHelperDefineCtrlInterface.m")
%%
%[text] ## Customization Example
%[text] For an example of how to customize the VTOL UAV controller template to model a different VTOL UAV configuration, see the [Model Alternative VTOL UAV Configuration](docid:uav_ug#mw_da03a27c-d322-4c45-9a35-652db4ce4c87) example.
%[text] Before resuming to other examples in this example series, you must close the `VTOLRefApp.prj` Simulink project by running this command in the Command Window:
%[text] `close(prj)`
%%
